<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Work-and-Tumble" class="currentChild" href="Work-and-Tumble">Work-and-Tumble</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In <a title="Prepress" href="Prepress">prepress</a> and printing, an <a title="Imposition" href="Imposition">imposition</a> or layout in which one plate contains all the images (pages) to be printed on both sides of a sheet. Once one side of a job has been printed, the pile of printed sheets is turned over, the edge of the sheet that was the <a title="Gripper Edge" href="Gripper_Edge">gripper edge</a> for the first side becoming the back edge for the second side. After printing, the sheet is cut in half, yielding two identical units. Work-and-tumble layouts, with their use of different gripper edges, may have <a title="Registration" href="Registration">registration</a> problems. See also <a title="Work-and-Turn" href="Work-and-Turn">Work-and-Turn</a> and <a title="Work-and-Twist" href="Work-and-Twist">Work-and-Twist</a>. Also known as <a title="Work-and-Flop" href="Work-and-Flop">work-and-flop</a> and <a title="Work-and-Roll" href="Work-and-Roll">work-and-roll</a>. 
</p>
